article.description: Andrea Lalum scored 18 points to lead  No. 24 Washington past Iowa State 76-55.
article.headline: Huskies shot 49 percent from the field
article.linkText: Cyclones suffer first home loss to No. 24 Washington
article.story:
AMES, Iowa (AP) -- Washington's sister act was too much for Iowa
State -- not to mention the Huskies' defense and outside shooting.

Sisters Giuliana and Gioconda Mendiola scored 16 points apiece,
Andrea Lalum had 18 and Washington made a season-high 10 3-pointers
in beating Iowa State 76-55 on Sunday.

The three seniors set the tone as Washington (7-2) attacked Iowa
State's 2-3 zone with crisp passes that led to open shots, usually
along the baseline. Lalum benefited from many of those passes and
shot 8-for-14, including two 3-pointers.

"My teammates found me. That's why I have to give the credit to
them," Lalum said. "Our offense is set to find people, but you
still have to get them the ball. You can be open and call for the
ball all you want, but if nobody gives it to you it doesn't do you
any good."

Giuliana Mendiola was from 2-for-3 from 3-point range and
7-for-10 overall. She also had six assists, six rebounds and two
steals. Gioconda Mendiola more than doubled her 7.4 scoring average
and made four 3-pointers.

"She made some open shots. When you're a senior, you make those
kind of plays," Iowa State coach Bill Fennelly said. "She and her
sister make for a good backcourt. They're tough kids, they're very
good players, they love to compete.

"When you have good guard play, you have a chance to be good,
especially when they're sisters. They're going to take care of each
other."

Washington played impressively despite a quick turnaround after
a disappointing 74-70 loss to No. 4 Texas Tech in Seattle on Friday
night. The Huskies flew to Iowa on Saturday and came out looking
fresh on Sunday.

They ran off 16 straight points while holding Iowa State
scoreless for more than 6 1/2 minutes to build a 28-13 lead and
were in control from then on.

"We had a tough game Friday night. We felt like we outplayed
them," Washington coach June Daugherty said. "You can sulk about
it for about one minute and then you've got to turn around and play
again. It was a confidence builder actually."

Anne O'Neil scored 20 points for Iowa State (5-4) and was the
Cyclones' only consistent threat. No one else had more than eight
points.

"They beat us in every area of the game," Fennelly said. "We
didn't have an answer for anything."
